@18   = ~Looking for a tomb.

While we were exploring the Bridge District we found Stivan, an halfling native of Athkatla, whom I asked for help in my search of Imoen and Irenicus. In exchange for a tomb where he might put the ashes of his close ones, Stivan offered us his guidance in his town and his defense against... er... seagulls. The halfling said I should go in the Government District and ask some clerk in the Council of Six.~
@19   = ~Looking for a tomb.

The clerk in the Council of Six Building has started the procedures required to make Stivan properly acquire the tomb. He promised he will send for us as soon as he is done, and also offered to keep the urn safe in the meantime.~
@20   = ~Looking for a tomb.

A clerk in the Council of Six Building explained us that there are currently no free tombs. However, he also mentioned that there is one where no one dares to tread because of voices about its inhabitant. Not scared by such tales, I decided to explore it: after cleaning it of any trouble I might find, in fact, we'd be free to claim it for Stivan's relatives..~
@21   = ~Looking for a tomb.

A messenger informed us that the documents for the transferal of the crypt are ready. I can go pick them up any time I wish from the clerk Lawrence in the Council of Six building.~
@22   = ~Looking for a tomb.

The urn containing the ashes of the Stivan's family broke before I could find a proper tomb for it. The halfling, furious, left the party.~
@23   = ~(Sigh) It doesn't seem real. I'm about to leave this urn behind. I'm about to give the final goodbye to my family...~
@24   = ~Come on, Stivan. Be strong.~
@25   = ~You aren't changing your mind, are you? I'd feel *slightly* disappointed if you decided to keep it with you.~
@26   = ~It's not a final goodbye. As long as the deceased live in our memories, they don't really die.~
@27   = ~It is just that the dead rest in peace. You can't imagine how much I would have wanted to properly bury Gorion...~
@28   = ~I didn't change my mind, <CHARNAME>, It's just...~
@29   = ~This *is* a final goodbye, <CHARNAME>! I... I lived too long trapped in the sorrow over my family's death! I... must go on!~
@30   = ~I... understand that your foster father's death was harsh on you, and that you wish you could have buried him, but...~
@31   = ~Do you think it easy? Do you think it easy to forever leave those that loved you behind? As soon as I leave their remains here, I... I will be alone!~
@32   = ~This is not true. You have many friends around you, me included.~
@33   = ~Your family disappeared many years ago, Stivan, not now.  All you're doing now is leaving their remains where they should have been for all this time.~
@34   = ~We're all alone. Use this experience to learn how to live for yourself.~
@35   = ~Are you telling me that that urn kept you company for all these years? No offense, friend, but this is silly. You have nothing but a silent object in your hands.~
@36   = ~(You see Stivan's eyes fill with tears).~
@37   = ~Oh, no. I beg you, don't cry. I can't comfort people...~
@38   = ~Let go, my friend. Cry as much as you wish.~
@39   = ~Men never cry, Stivan. Dry your eyes, come on.~
@40   = ~So even men cry. Surprising.~
@41   = ~(Stivan explodes in tears, holding you close). *SOB*!~
@42   = ~(The halfling cries for many minutes, holding your venter in his arms. You hear him whisper something).~
@43   = ~Mommy...~
@44   = ~ (You stay silent).~
@45   = ~ (You hold him close).~
@46   = ~Shh... It's all right.~
@47   = ~Leave me, Stivan. You're making me uneasy.~
@48   = ~Daddy...~
@49   = ~(After some moments, the halfling slowly leaves your embrace, drying the tears that wet his face).~
@50   = ~Heh. It'd be better if I hurried up.~
@51   = ~Looking for a tomb.

We finally managed to leave the ashes of Stivan's familiars in the crypt. To thank me, he gifted me his "most precious treasure", a strange red plume taken from a seagull.~
@52   = ~(The halfling abruptly leaves you, drying the tears that wet his face).~
@53   = ~(Snort!) Your heart is colder than stone!~
@54   = ~(Stivan runs to the end of the crypt and puts the urn inside the chest. He also puts something else near the container).~
@55   = ~Mommy... Daddy... Brothers... Goodbye.~
@56   = ~(Sniff) One day Minsc will properly bury sweet Dynaheir as well. Her resting place will be so majestic that hamsters will rush from all over Faerun to honor her!~
@57   = ~I don't understand why townspeople feel the need to bury the dead in such restrictive places. Nature offers many a place that would be better for this task.~
@58   = ~Tombs aren't mere holding places for the bodies of the dead. They are also needed to comfort the soul of those who remain alive.~
@59   = ~Now that you put the physical weight of your tragedy behind, our walk nears its end. The last mile awaits us.~
@60   = ~I-I'm... I'm happy for you, Stivan...~
@61   = ~Might nobody disturb your eternal rest, halfling friends.~
@62   = ~I appreciate the essentiality of your last goodbyes with them, Stivan. You should be taken as example by all those nobles that waste treasures in needlessly wealthy funeral rites.~
@63   = ~Really moving. Had I a heart, I'd be crying.~
@64   = ~Ahh... Life is the most boring of adventures. It always ends the same way.~
@65   = ~Will you keep going like this for much more, sakphul?~
@66   = ~I haven't seen many things in my life, but death is the one I saw the most often.~
@67   = ~I can never recall: is it bad form to tell licentious stories during a funeral?~
@68   = ~I... I... I'm sorry, Stivan. I don't know what else to say...~
@69   = ~Hmph. I hate these melodramatic moments. Does anyone want to go bash someone in the head?~
@70   = ~We're all peers before death, so... if you were just, might Torm accept you in His house.~
@71   = ~Might the light of Helm guide their souls to peace.~
@72   = ~It might be trite to express condolences in these moments, but know that I understand your loss better than anyone else.~
@73   = ~*Ahem* You should know, <CHARNAME>, that the chest is trapped to avoid looters disturbing my loved ones. Whomever would be fool enough to mess with it, he'd be drowned in seagull poo and plumes. Diabolic, eh?~
@74   = ~To thank you for the help, I want to gift you something. Here: my most precious treasure.~
@75   = ~It's a red plume. I found it some time ago while depluming a seagull. Really strange, since they are exclusively white, possibly with some black or gray spots.~
@76   = ~Speaking about seagulls, I think I heard one. Could they be besting even here in the Graveyard District?! Let's rush out and check!~
@77   = ~Eeeekkkk! That wasn't a seagull!~
@78   = ~Damn you... You violated our Lord's tomb!~
